│        "topic_title": "Container registries (ECR)",                               │
│        "theory_explanation": "You've built your amazing Docker container image –  │
│  it's perfectly packaged and ready to go! But where do you store it so that ECS,  │
│  Fargate, or even your teammates can easily find and pull it when they need to    │
│  run your application? You need a digital library or warehouse for your           │
│  container images!\n\nThat's precisely what a **container registry** is. It's a   │
│  centralized service designed to store, manage, and distribute your Docker        │
│  images. Think of it like GitHub, but specifically for Docker images instead of   │
│  code.\n\n**Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR)** is AWS'ss fully managed     │
│  container registry. It integrates seamlessly with other AWS services like ECS    │
│  and Fargate, making the deployment process smooth and secure.\n\nHere's why ECR  │
│  (or any container registry) is crucial:\n*   **Centralized Storage:** All your   │
│  Docker images are in one secure, accessible place.\n*   **Version Control:**     │
│  You can store different versions of your images (e.g., `my-app:v1`,              │
│  `my-app:v2`, `my-app:latest`), allowing for easy rollbacks or testing new        │
│  features.\n*   **Security:** ECR provides secure access control, ensuring only   │
│  authorized users or services can push or pull your images.\n*                    │
│  **Integration:** It works hand-in-hand with ECS and Fargate, so when you create  │
│  a Task Definition, you simply point to your image in ECR, and ECS knows exactly  │
│  where to find it.\n\nFor a hobbyist, ECR simplifies the process of getting your  │
│  container images ready for deployment on AWS. You build your image locally,      │
│  push it to ECR, and then ECS/Fargate can pull it from there to run your          │
│  application. The video and AWS documentation will guide you through using ECR    │
