│        "topic_title": "Amazon CloudWatch Metrics",                                │
│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine you're building a cool new gadget for your  │
│  hobby project. How do you know if it's working well? Is its battery running      │
│  low? Is it getting too hot? You'd probably want little gauges or indicators to   │
│  tell you these things, right?\n\nThat's exactly what **Amazon CloudWatch         │
│  Metrics** are for your AWS resources! A **metric** is simply a time-ordered set  │
│  of data points that represents a variable you want to monitor. Think of it like  │
│  a speedometer for your car, a temperature gauge for your computer, or a counter  │
│  for how many times your website has been visited.\n\nCloudWatch automatically    │
│  collects these metrics from many AWS services (like how busy your server is, or  │
│  how much data your storage is using). You can also send your own custom metrics  │
│  from your applications!\n\nEach metric has a few key components:\n*              │
│  **Namespace:** This is like a folder that organizes related metrics. For         │
│  example, all your EC2 server metrics might live in the `AWS/EC2` namespace.\n*   │
│  **Metric Name:** The specific thing you're measuring, like `CPUUtilization` or   │
│  `DiskReadBytes`.\n*   **Dimensions:** These are key-value pairs that help you    │
│  filter and refine your metrics. For instance, `InstanceId=i-1234567890abcdef0`   │
│  would let you see the CPU utilization for a *specific* server.\n\n**Why is this  │
│  useful for your hobby project?** If you're running a small website or a game     │
│  server on AWS, metrics let you peek under the hood to see if everything is       │
│  running smoothly. Are people actually using your app? Is your server             │
│  struggling? Metrics give you the answers!\n\nThe provided article dives deeper   │
│  into these concepts, and the video will show you how to see and work with these  │
│  metrics in the AWS console.",                                                    │
