│        "theory_explanation": "So you're collecting all these valuable logs with   │
│  CloudWatch Logs. But what if you have multiple applications, or different parts  │
│  of the same application, all sending logs? It could quickly become a messy pile  │
│  of notes!\n\nThis is where **Log Groups** and **Log Streams** come in to         │
│  organize everything beautifully. Think of it like a library:\n*   A **Log        │
│  Group** is like a specific shelf or section in the library, dedicated to logs    │
│  from a particular application or service. For example, you might have a          │
│  `MyWebsite-Frontend` Log Group and a `MyWebsite-Backend` Log Group. This helps   │
│  you keep logs from different sources completely separate and easy to find.\n*    │
│  A **Log Stream** is like an individual book on that shelf. Within a Log Group,   │
│  a Log Stream represents a sequence of log events from a specific source. For     │
│  instance, if you have multiple servers running your website, each server might   │
│  send its logs to its own Log Stream within the `MyWebsite-Frontend` Log Group.   │
│  All log events within a stream are ordered by time.\n\n**Why is this useful for  │
│  your hobby project?** This structure makes it incredibly easy to navigate and    │
│  analyze your logs. If you're debugging an issue on your frontend, you just go    │
│  to the `MyWebsite-Frontend` Log Group. If you want to see logs from a specific   │
│  server that might be misbehaving, you find its Log Stream. It's all about        │
│  keeping your digital \"notebooks\" neat and tidy!\n\nThe provided article        │
│  explains in detail how to create and manage these organizational structures for  │
│  your logs.",                                                                     │
