│        "topic_title": "CloudWatch Dashboards",                                    │
│        "theory_explanation": "You've got metrics telling you how busy your        │
│  server is, alarms ready to warn you if things go wrong, and logs capturing       │
│  every detail. That's a lot of information! But wouldn't it be great to see all   │
│  the most important stuff at a glance, like a custom control panel for your       │
│  hobby project?\n\nThat's exactly what **CloudWatch Dashboards** are! A           │
│  dashboard is a customizable home screen where you can visualize your key         │
│  metrics, log data, and alarm states all in one place. You can add widgets        │
│  (little blocks) to display:\n*   Graphs of your server's CPU utilization over    │
│  time.\n*   Numbers showing how many errors your application has logged.\n*       │
│  The current status of your alarms (e.g., `OK`, `ALARM`).\n*   Even text notes    │
│  to remind yourself or others about specific details.\n\nYou can arrange these    │
│  widgets however you like, making it easy to monitor the health and performance   │
│  of your AWS resources and applications without having to jump between different  │
│  screens.\n\n**Why is this useful for your hobby project?** Instead of clicking   │
│  around to check different metrics or log groups, a dashboard gives you a         │
│  single, unified view of your project's health. It's perfect for quickly          │
│  checking if everything is running smoothly, especially if you're running         │
│  multiple services. It's your personal mission control center!\n\nThe             │
│  documentation provides instructions on how to create these personalized          │
