│        "topic_title": "EventBridge (CloudWatch Events) basics",                   │
│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine you're running a small online store for     │
│  your hobby. When a customer places an order, you want several things to happen   │
│  automatically: send a confirmation email, update your inventory, and maybe even  │
│  notify your shipping partner. How do you make all these different pieces talk    │
│  to each other and react to that \"order placed\" event?\n\nThis is where         │
│  **EventBridge** (which evolved from what was previously known as CloudWatch      │
│  Events) comes in! Think of EventBridge as a central post office or a             │
│  super-smart dispatcher for your AWS services. Instead of services directly       │
│  talking to each other, they send \"events\" (like a letter or a package) to      │
│  EventBridge.\n\nAn **event** is simply a record of a change in state or a user   │
│  action. For example:\n*   An AWS service tells EventBridge: \"An EC2 instance    │
│  just started!\"\n*   Your application tells EventBridge: \"A new order was just  │
│  placed!\"\n*   A scheduled timer tells EventBridge: \"It's 3 AM, time to run     │
│  the daily backup!\"\n\nEventBridge then looks at the \"address\" on that event   │
│  (called an **event pattern**) and routes it to the correct **target** (the       │
│  recipient). A target could be another AWS service like a Lambda function (to     │
│  send an email), an SQS queue, or even an HTTP endpoint outside of AWS.\n\n**Why  │
│  is this useful for your hobby project?** EventBridge allows you to build highly  │
│  decoupled, event-driven architectures. Instead of your application having to     │
│  know about every single service it needs to interact with, it just emits an      │
│  event. EventBridge handles the \"who needs to know about this?\" part. This      │
│  makes your applications more flexible, easier to scale, and simpler to manage    │
│  as your hobby project grows. It's a powerful way to automate workflows and       │
│  react to changes across your AWS environment.\n\nThe documentation clarifies     │
│  the evolution from CloudWatch Events to EventBridge and its capabilities, while  │
│  the video provides both theory and a demo to help you grasp this concept.",      │
