│        "topic_title": "CloudWatch Alarms",                                        │
│        "theory_explanation": "Okay, so you have all these awesome metrics         │
│  telling you what's happening. But what if you're not constantly watching them?   │
│  What if your server suddenly gets overloaded in the middle of the night? You     │
│  wouldn't know until it's too late!\n\nThis is where **CloudWatch Alarms** come   │
│  to the rescue! Think of an alarm like a smart smoke detector for your AWS        │
│  resources. You tell it: \"If this metric (like server CPU usage) goes above a    │
│  certain level (say, 80%) for a specific amount of time (like 5 minutes), then    │
│  *do something*!\"\n\nThat \"do something\" can be incredibly powerful. It        │
│  could:\n*   Send you an email or a text message.\n*   Automatically scale up     │
│  your server capacity.\n*   Trigger another AWS service to perform a specific     │
│  action, like restarting a problematic application.\n\nYou define a               │
│  **threshold** (the limit), a **period** (how long the metric needs to be         │
│  over/under the threshold), and an **action**. When the metric crosses that       │
│  threshold for the specified period, the alarm changes its state (e.g., from      │
│  `OK` to `ALARM`), and the action is triggered.\n\n**Why is this useful for your  │
│  hobby project?** You can set up alarms to notify you if your website goes down,  │
│  if your database is running out of space, or if your costs are unexpectedly      │
│  spiking. It gives you peace of mind, knowing that CloudWatch is watching your    │
│  back even when you're not.\n\nThe documentation shows you how to set up these    │
│  powerful guardians, and the video provides a step-by-step guide to creating      │
│  them.",                                                                          │
