│        "topic_title": "What is Serverless?",                                      │
│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine you want to host a small party.\n*          │
│  **Traditional Approach:** You'd buy a house (your server), furnish it (install   │
│  software), maintain it (fix leaks, pay electricity), and pay for it 24/7, even   │
│  if no one's there. You're responsible for *everything*.\n*   **Serverless        │
│  Approach:** You rent a party room *only for the hours you need it*. The venue    │
│  owner (the cloud provider like AWS) handles the building, electricity,           │
│  cleaning, and maintenance. You just show up, have your party, and pay *only for  │
│  the time you used the room*.\n\nServerless computing doesn't mean \"no           │
│  servers.\" It means *you* don't manage them. A cloud provider handles all the    │
│  underlying infrastructure – provisioning, scaling, maintenance, and patching.    │
│  You just write your code, upload it, and it runs when triggered. You pay only    │
│  for the compute time your code consumes, not for idle servers. This lets you     │
│  focus purely on building your application's logic, making development faster     │
│  and often cheaper for many use cases.",                                          │
