│        "topic_title": "AWS Lambda functions",                                     │
│        "theory_explanation": "Think of AWS Lambda as a highly specialized,        │
│  super-efficient robot chef. You give it a recipe (your code) and tell it what    │
│  ingredient (an \"event\") to look for. When that ingredient appears, the robot   │
│  chef instantly wakes up, executes your recipe, and then goes back to sleep,      │
│  costing you nothing while idle.\n\nAWS Lambda is the heart of serverless         │
│  computing on AWS. It's a \"Functions as a Service\" (FaaS) offering that lets    │
│  you run your code without provisioning or managing servers. You package your     │
│  application logic into a function (e.g., a Python script, a Node.js file),       │
│  define what triggers it (an \"event\"), and Lambda takes care of everything      │
│  else. It automatically scales your function up or down based on demand,          │
│  ensuring your code runs reliably whether you have one user or a million.",       │
