│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine a busy coffee shop where every action is    │
│  an \"event.\" When a customer orders a coffee (event), it triggers the barista   │
│  to make it (action). When the coffee is ready (another event), it triggers the   │
│  pickup notification. Each part of the system reacts to specific events without   │
│  needing to know the intricate details of other parts.\n\nEvent-driven            │
│  architecture is a powerful way to design systems where different parts           │
│  (components) communicate by sending and receiving \"events.\" An event is        │
│  simply a signal that something notable has happened (e.g., a new user signed     │
│  up, a file was uploaded, an order was placed). Instead of components directly    │
│  calling each other, they publish events, and other components \"listen\" for     │
│  events they care about and react accordingly. This makes systems highly          │
│  flexible, scalable, and easier to maintain because components are loosely        │
│  coupled – they don't depend heavily on each other's internal workings.",         │
