│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine Amazon S3 (Simple Storage Service) as a     │
│  massive, infinitely scalable digital storage locker facility. You can rent       │
│  \"lockers\" (called **buckets**) and store any kind of \"stuff\" (called         │
│  **objects**, which are essentially files) inside them. S3 is perfect for         │
│  storing website images, backups, documents, or data for your hobby               │
│  projects.\n\nWith Boto3, your Python script becomes the ultimate manager for     │
│  this storage facility. You can programmatically:\n*   **Create new buckets:**    │
│  Set up a new storage locker.\n*   **Upload objects:** Put your files into a      │
│  specific bucket.\n*   **Download objects:** Retrieve files from a bucket.\n*     │
│  **List bucket contents:** See what files are inside a locker.\n*   **Delete      │
│  objects/buckets:** Remove files or even entire lockers.\n\nThis means you can    │
│  automate tasks like backing up your local project files to S3, serving static    │
│  website content, or processing data stored in the cloud, all without ever        │
│  manually clicking through the AWS console.\n\n**Bridge to Resources:** The       │
│  official Boto3 documentation for S3 and the video tutorial will walk you         │
│  through practical examples, showing you the specific Boto3 commands (methods)    │
│  to perform these S3 operations. You'll see how to create a `boto3.client('s3')`  │
│  object and then use its methods like `upload_file()`, `download_file()`, and     │
│  `list_objects_v2()`.",                                                           │
