│        "topic_title": "Error handling in Boto3",                                  │
│        "theory_explanation": "Even the most perfectly written script can          │
│  encounter issues when talking to a remote service like AWS. What if you try to   │
│  access an S3 bucket that doesn't exist? Or you don't have permission to start    │
│  an EC2 instance? Or there's a temporary network glitch? Without proper error     │
│  handling, your Python script might just crash and stop working, which isn't      │
│  very helpful!\n\n**Error handling** is like giving your script a plan B (or C,   │
│  or D!) for when things don't go as expected. In Python, this primarily involves  │
│  using `try` and `except` blocks. You put the code that might cause an error      │
│  inside a `try` block. If an error (an \"exception\") occurs, Python \"catches\"  │
│  it, and the code inside the corresponding `except` block is executed instead of  │
│  your program crashing.\n\nBoto3 errors often come in the form of a               │
│  `ClientError` (or other Boto3-specific exceptions). These `ClientError`          │
│  exceptions contain valuable information, including an error code (like           │
│  `NoSuchBucket` or `UnauthorizedOperation`) and a message, which helps you        │
│  understand exactly what went wrong. By catching these specific errors, your      │
│  script can:\n*   Print a user-friendly message instead of a technical            │
│  traceback.\n*   Attempt to retry the operation.\n*   Log the error for later     │
│  review.\n*   Take an alternative action.\n\nRobust error handling makes your     │
│  Boto3 scripts more reliable, resilient, and user-friendly, especially important  │
│  for hobby projects that might run unattended.\n\n**Bridge to Resources:** The    │
│  official Boto3 documentation on error handling and the video guide will show     │
│  you how to implement `try...except` blocks effectively with Boto3, how to        │
│  inspect `ClientError` exceptions for specific details, and how to write more     │
│  robust cloud automation scripts.",                                               │
