│      "theory_explanation": "While Cost Explorer helps you *see* your spending,    │
│  AWS Budgets helps you *control* it. Think of AWS Budgets as setting a spending   │
│  limit on your credit card or creating a household budget. It's a service that    │
│  allows you to set custom budgets for your AWS costs and usage, and then receive  │
│  alerts when you're approaching or exceeding those limits.\n\nHere's how it       │
│  works:\n\n1.  **Set Your Budget:** You define a specific amount of money you     │
│  want to spend (or usage you want to consume) for a given period (e.g., $10 per   │
│  month).\n2.  **Choose What to Track:** You can budget for your overall AWS       │
│  spending, or get more granular – for a specific service (like EC2), a            │
│  particular region, or even individual resource tags.\n3.  **Set Up Alerts:**     │
│  This is the magic part! You can configure alerts to notify you via email or SNS  │
│  (a notification service) when:\n    *   Your actual costs exceed a certain       │
│  percentage of your budget (e.g., 80% of your $10 budget).\n    *   Your          │
│  forecasted costs are predicted to exceed your budget.\n    *   Your actual       │
│  usage exceeds a certain threshold (e.g., you've used 90% of your free tier EC2   │
│  hours).\n\n**Why it matters for you:** For hobby projects, AWS Budgets is a      │
│  crucial safety net. It prevents \"bill shock\" by giving you an early warning    │
│  if your experiments are getting too expensive. You can quickly react,            │
│  investigate with Cost Explorer, and adjust your resources before costs spiral    │
│  out of control. It empowers you to experiment freely, knowing you have           │
│  guardrails in place.\n\nThe provided resources will guide you through setting    │
│  up your first budget and configuring alerts, giving you peace of mind as you     │
