│      {                                                                            │
│        "topic_title": "Security Best Practices",                                  │
│        "theory_explanation": "Securing your AWS account isn't a one-time task;    │
│  it's an ongoing journey, much like keeping your home safe. You don't just lock   │
│  the front door once and forget about it; you check windows, maintain your        │
│  alarm, and are mindful of who you let in. **AWS Security Best Practices** are a  │
│  set of guidelines and actions to help you keep your cloud resources safe and     │
│  sound.\nFor a hobbyist, these practices are about building good habits from the  │
│  start:\n1.  **Never Use Your Root Account for Daily Tasks:** Your AWS \"root     │
│  account\" is like the master key to your entire house – it has ultimate power.   │
│  You should only use it for initial setup and very rare, specific tasks. For      │
│  everything else, create an IAM user for yourself and assign it only the          │
│  permissions it needs.\n2.  **Implement the Principle of Least Privilege:** This  │
│  is a golden rule! It means giving users, groups, and roles only the minimum      │
│  permissions necessary to perform their specific job, and nothing more. If your   │
│  \"Decoration Team\" only needs to access painting supplies, don't give them      │
│  keys to the entire workshop! This limits potential damage if an account is       │
│  compromised.\n3.  **Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) Everywhere:** As    │
│  discussed, MFA is your best friend. Enable it for your root account and all IAM  │
│  users. It's a simple, yet incredibly effective, security measure.\n4.            │
│  **Monitor and Log Everything:** AWS provides services like CloudTrail and        │
