│        "topic_title": "What is Cloud Computing?",                                 │
│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine you want to build a cool new app or host a  │
│  website for your hobby project. Traditionally, you'd need to buy your own        │
│  computer servers, set them up in a special room, manage their power, cooling,    │
│  and internet connection. It's like building your own power plant just to power   │
│  your house!\n\n**Cloud Computing** is like plugging into a massive, shared       │
│  power grid instead. Instead of owning and maintaining all that expensive         │
│  computer hardware yourself, you \"rent\" computing resources—like virtual        │
│  computers (servers), storage space, databases, and networking—over the internet  │
│  from a third-party provider, such as Amazon Web Services (AWS).\n\nThink of it   │
│  this way:\n*   **Traditional:** You buy a physical server, install software,     │
│  and keep it running 24/7 in your home or office. If your project gets popular,   │
│  you need to buy *more* servers. If it's quiet, your expensive server sits        │
│  idle.\n*   **Cloud:** You simply tell AWS, \"Hey, I need a virtual computer for  │
│  a few hours,\" or \"I need some storage for my photos.\" They provide it         │
│  instantly, and you only pay for what you use, much like your electricity bill.   │
│  If your hobby website suddenly gets a lot of visitors, you can easily ask for    │
│  more computing power, and then scale back down when things quieten.\n\nIt's      │
│  about getting computing power, storage, and other services **on-demand**,        │
│  paying only for what you consume, and letting someone else handle the heavy      │
│  lifting of maintaining the physical infrastructure. This frees you up to focus   │
│  on building your awesome projects!",                                             │
